				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kahruvel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1356177); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1356177&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182925" alt="Kahruvel" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1356177)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kahruvel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1356177); return false;" >Kahruvel</a></span> <span class="odate time_1337039715 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 May 2012 23:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1448891">
									

<p>Keter, perhaps?</p>
<p>As asked before, is it possible for SCP-676 to consume the planet if not continuously sated? The SCP also does not pass the &quot;locked box&quot; test very well, given the fact that it cannot be contained in a laboratory setting. In fact, containing it requires a continuous resource which may not always be readily available.</p>
<p>It will hit the river. If that dries up, maybe a lake. Then, the lake may become affected with the dissolving trait, while slowly being drained. And if it expands to include an ocean&#8230; well, think about it. That's an ocean that dissolves everything that comes into contact with it. There's no way to tell if the water being drained is recirculated back out, or simply&#8230; vanishing.</p>
<p>There's no known limit to this thing, is what I'm getting at. XK-Class end-of-the-world scenario?</p>

							</div>

								
